prose-invert"><h2>Understanding the axis of symmetry</h2><p>The axis of sym=
metry is a fundamental concept in algebra and geometry. For parabolas, it's=
 a vertical line that divides the curve into two identical halves. Every po=
int on one side of this line has a mirror point on the other side at the sa=
me distance from the axis.</p><h3>Key concepts</h3><ul><li><strong>Axis of =
symmetry formula:</strong> For a parabola in standard form y =3D ax=C2=B2 +=
 bx + c, the axis of symmetry is always x =3D -b/(2a). This vertical line p=
asses through the vertex of the parabola.</li><li><strong>Vertex coordinate=
s:</strong> The vertex is the point where the parabola reaches its maximum =
or minimum value. Its x-coordinate is -b/(2a), and the y-coordinate is foun=
d by substituting this x value back into the original equation.</li><li><st=
rong>Vertex form:</strong> The equation y =3D a(x - h)=C2=B2 + k reveals th=
e vertex (h, k) directly. Converting from standard form to vertex form make=
s it easier to identify the parabola's key features.</li><li><strong>Parabo=
la direction:</strong> If a &gt; 0, the parabola opens upward and has a min=
imum point at the vertex. If a &lt; 0, it opens downward with a maximum poi=
nt at the vertex.</li><li><strong>Other conic sections:</strong> Ellipses h=
ave two axes of symmetry (major and minor axes), while hyperbolas also have=
 two perpendicular axes of symmetry through their center.</li></ul><h3>How =
to use this calculator</h3><ol><li>Select the shape type (parabola, ellipse=
, or hyperbola)</li><li>For parabolas, enter the coefficients a, b, and c f=
rom the standard form y =3D ax=C2=B2 + bx + c</li><li>Click "Calculate" to =
see the axis of symmetry, vertex coordinates, and vertex form</li><li>Revie=
w the step-by-step solution to understand the calculation process</li></ol>=
<h3>Example calculations</h3><p><strong>Example 1:</strong> For the parabol=
a y =3D 2x=C2=B2 + 8x + 5:</p><ul><li>a =3D 2, b =3D 8, c =3D 5</li><li>Axi=
s of symmetry: x =3D -8/(2=C3=972) =3D -8/4 =3D -2</li><li>Vertex x-coordin=
ate: -2</li><li>Vertex y-coordinate: 2(-2)=C2=B2 + 8(-2) + 5 =3D 8 - 16 + 5=
 =3D -3</li><li>Vertex: (-2, -3)</li><li>Vertex form: y =3D 2(x + 2)=C2=B2 =
- 3</li></ul><p><strong>Example 2:</strong> For the parabola y =3D -x=C2=B2=
 + 6x - 5:</p><ul><li>a =3D -1, b =3D 6, c =3D -5</li><li>Axis of symmetry:=
 x =3D -6/(2=C3=97(-1)) =3D -6/(-2) =3D 3</li><li>Vertex x-coordinate: 3</l=
i><li>Vertex y-coordinate: -(3)=C2=B2 + 6(3) - 5 =3D -9 + 18 - 5 =3D 4</li>=
<li>Vertex: (3, 4)</li><li>Vertex form: y =3D -(x - 3)=C2=B2 + 4</li></ul><=
h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3><h4>What is the axis of symmetry?</h4><p>=
The axis of symmetry is a vertical line that divides a parabola into two mi=
rror images. For a parabola in the form y =3D ax=C2=B2 + bx + c, the axis o=
f symmetry is x =3D -b/(2a). This line passes through the vertex of the par=
abola.</p><h4>How do you find the axis of symmetry?</h4><p>For a quadratic =
function y =3D ax=C2=B2 + bx + c, use the formula x =3D -b/(2a). The coeffi=
cients a and b come from the standard form of the equation. For example, in=
 y =3D 2x=C2=B2 + 4x + 1, a =3D 2 and b =3D 4, so the axis of symmetry is x=
 =3D -4/(2=C3=972) =3D -1.</p><h4>What is vertex form?</h4><p>Vertex form i=
s y =3D a(x - h)=C2=B2 + k, where (h, k) is the vertex of the parabola. The=
 axis of symmetry is x =3D h. Converting from standard form to vertex form =
helps identify the parabola's maximum or minimum point and its line of symm=
etry.</p><h4>Do ellipses have an axis of symmetry?</h4><p>Yes, ellipses hav=
e two axes of symmetry: the major axis (longest diameter) and the minor axi=
s (shortest diameter). These axes are perpendicular to each other and inter=
sect at the center of the ellipse.</p><h4>Can the axis of symmetry be horiz=
ontal?</h4><p>For standard parabolas of the form y =3D ax=C2=B2 + bx + c, t=
he axis of symmetry is always vertical. However, for parabolas that open ho=
rizontally (of the form x =3D ay=C2=B2 + by + c), the axis of symmetry woul=
d be horizontal.</p></div></div><footer class=3D"bg-white dark:bg-gray-950"=
